<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-446-783  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 446 783.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lotus  Sept 1990 v6 n9 p20(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Lotus Publishing Corp. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hacker challenge. (TraqNet security system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   LeeMah Datacom Security Corp. (products).andO;Product:   LeeMah DataCom Security TraqNet 2000 (Data security equipment)(design and construction).andO;Topic:     Access ControlsData SecuritySecurity Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Hacker ChallengeandM;As a gimmick, it was topnotch.andP;  LeeMah DataCom Security Corp., in Hayward,Calif., put its Traqnet security system into operation on a computer at KPMGPeat Marwick in Atlanta and publicly dared the nation's hackers to break in.andO;In just a week, hackers made 7,476 attempts--all unsuccessful.andM;Since the hacker challenge, LeeMah's sales have boomed, says President JohnTuomy, who came up with the idea.andP;  The TraqNet 2001 system uses a tokendevice called the InfoKey, which uses an encryption algorithm specified bythe Department of Defense.andP;  Each authorized user carries his own token.andP;  Toaccess the protected system, a user can plug the token into any modem.andP;  TheTraqNet 2001 system queries the InfoKey before the user is allowed to enter apassword.andM;&quot;It effectively gives you the same security you'd have on a leased line, atdial-up costs,&quot; Tuomy claims.andP;  The price, including a receiving box on theprotected computer and a token for each authorized user, runs about $1,000for one line and up to $14,000 for 32 lines.andO;</TEXT></DOC>